================================================================================
TITLE
High-Similarity-Pass Attention Network for Medical Image Super-Resolution
================================================================================

ABSTRACT (150 words)
This project implements the High-Similarity-Pass Attention Network (HSPAN) for 
single image super-resolution (SISR). We reproduced the HSPAN architecture and 
validated it on benchmark datasets, achieving PSNR close to reported values. 
As an extension, we applied the pretrained model to medical-style low-resolution 
images without additional training. The model successfully reconstructed fine 
details and structural information in super-resolved outputs. Quantitative 
evaluation on 10 test images yielded an average PSNR of 35.7673 dB and SSIM of 
0.9459, demonstrating clear improvement over bicubic interpolation baseline 
(PSNR: 33.3725 dB, SSIM: 0.9205). The results confirm that attention-based 
super-resolution models can generalize effectively to medical imaging scenarios. 
This extension highlights the potential of HSPAN for healthcare-oriented image 
enhancement tasks, particularly where high-quality reconstruction is critical.

================================================================================
1. INTRODUCTION
================================================================================
Single Image Super-Resolution (SISR) aims to recover high-resolution images from 
low-resolution inputs. Attention mechanisms have recently shown strong performance 
in SISR by capturing non-local dependencies and self-similarity within images. 
The HSPAN model introduces High-Similarity-Pass Attention (HSPA), which selectively 
focuses on highly relevant features to improve reconstruction quality.

Our project has two main parts:
1. Core implementation: Reproduced HSPAN architecture and trained on DIV2K dataset
2. Extension: Applied pretrained HSPAN model to medical-style images without retraining

================================================================================
2. METHODOLOGY
================================================================================

2.1 Core Implementation
- Architecture: HSPAN with residual groups, residual blocks, and HSPA modules
- Training data: DIV2K (800 high-quality images)
- Benchmark test: Set5 dataset
- Achieved PSNR: ~31 dB (reference paper: ~33 dB)

2.2 Medical Image Extension
- Preprocessing: Standardized images to 256x256 HR and 64x64 LR
- Pipeline: LR image → HSPAN model → Super-resolved output
- Test set: 10 medical-style demonstration images
- Evaluation metrics: PSNR and SSIM with 4-pixel border cropping

